subject: HISTORY

subject: HISTORY
text: The Friars.

subject: HISTORY

subject: HISTORY

subject: HISTORY
text: Plebiscite.

subject: HISTORY
text: Compare the services of St. Columba to Scotland with the services of St. Augustine to England.

subject: HISTORY
text: “The character of the monarch determined the character of the reign.” Discuss this statement with reference to any three of the following: William the Conqueror; John; Edward II.; Mary, Queen of Scots; George IV.

subject: HISTORY
text: Compare the sources of English wealth in the Middle Ages and in the 19th century.

subject: HISTORY
text: The following battles are commonly described as “decisive.” What issue did each of them decide? Bannockburn, Bosworth, Naseby, Plassey, Trafalgar, Leipzig.

subject: HISTORY
text: “If that you will France win, Then with Scotland first begin.” How far does this adage actually represent English policy between 1414 and 1560?

subject: HISTORY
text: The reign of Elizabeth is often described as the most adventurous period of English history. Illustrate this from the careers of any two famous soldiers or sailors of the reign of Elizabeth.

subject: HISTORY
text: What objects did Charles II. keep before him in

subject: HISTORY
text: his foreign and

subject: HISTORY
text: his domestic policy, and how far did he succeed in attaining these objects?

subject: HISTORY
text: What reasons entitle any three of the following to be described as Empire-builders: Cromwell, Chatham, Warren Hastings, Captain Cook, James Watt, Lord Dalhousie, Cecil Rhodes?

subject: HISTORY
text: Discuss one of the following topics:

subject: HISTORY
text: The growth of religious toleration since

subject: HISTORY
text: 19th century factory legislation.

subject: HISTORY
text: The relations of the United Kingdom with France and with Germany in the reigns of Queen Victoria and Edward VII.
